{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"044f1238-5939-443d-a34a-ec7286978de2","content":"**The problem: MAUI has no \"request\" scope.**\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` ties the lifetime to an **HTTP request** — each request gets a fresh `DbContext`. In MAUI, there's no equivalent concept. The app is a single long-running process, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` is created once and reused forever, accumulating tracked entities across navigations.\n\n**Fixes (pick one):**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — each injection gets a new instance. Simplest fix.\n\n2. **Use an `IDbContextFactory`:**\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>(opts =>\n       opts.UseSqlite(\"...\"));\n   ```\n   Then inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>` and create short-lived contexts:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\n3. **Manually manage scope** with `IServiceScopeFactory` per page/operation.\n\nOption 2 (factory) is the recommended pattern for non-HTTP apps like MAUI, Blazor Desktop, and WPF.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a4fbd180-022d-4773-bc9c-f7af54addcde","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scopes and DbContext lifetime. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no \"request\" — the app is one long-running process, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. The DbContext lives for the entire app lifetime, causing stale/persisted data across navigations.","outputTokens":446},"id":"54609ff5-892a-4cb2-90cd-37b560023bbb","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:43:13.509Z","parentId":"36d012ab-e695-45e2-ab20-41aeb000d1f5"}
